  "method": "We propose an inference-time pipeline that transforms a large set of frozen visual tokens into a compact, text-conditioned memory without changing the vision encoder or retraining. First, run the frozen vision encoder as usual to obtain N patch tokens. Before decoding begins (or after the first 1–2 generated tokens), perform a cheap probing pass that uses the model’s existing cross-attention to accumulate a per-token importance score by summing attention mass to each visual token across layers/heads and weighting by the token’s value-norm. In parallel, build a spatially-regularized similarity graph in the visual feature space (nearest-neighbor links constrained by patch adjacency). This gives two signals: token salience (text-conditioned) and token redundancy (feature-similarity + spatial proximity).\n\nNext, adaptively choose a target visual budget r << N based on a global image-dependency gauge: compute a prompt-dependency measure once every few decoding steps by comparing the next-token distribution with and without the visual prompt (e.g., using a symmetric f-divergence). When dependency is high (e.g., early steps, fine-grained queries), keep a larger budget; as dependency fades during generation, shrink r more aggressively. Given r, prune the lowest-salience tokens while enforcing coverage: retain at least one representative per connected region in the similarity graph via farthest-point sampling in feature space, ensuring small but important objects are not lost. Then merge the remaining tokens into r “supertokens” by attention-aware aggregation: for each cross-attention layer/head, form new keys/values as convex combinations of the original tokens within each cluster, using normalized weights proportional to their accumulated attention mass (fallback to uniform if no mass yet). Replace the visual KV cache with these r per-layer supertoken KV tensors and continue decoding.\n\nFor later decoding stages, optionally switch from token clusters to a tiny set of virtual conditioning slots that approximate the effect of all visual tokens. Construct M << r virtual slots per cross-attention layer by solving a per-instance low-rank approximation of the token-space: compute the top-M components of the attention-weighted token covariance for keys and values, and instantiate virtual K,V as these components scaled to match the first and second moments of the original K,V under current attention. Inject these virtual slots as a fixed “visual prefix memory” so subsequent steps attend to a constant, tiny set, eliminating further attention over spatial tokens while preserving conditioning.\n\nTo keep quality stable, employ a conservative guardrail: after each pruning/merging event, evaluate the dependency gauge on the next step; if it drops below a user-specified threshold (indicating visual influence was over-removed) or the next-token log-probability degrades beyond a small tolerance, partially roll back by restoring the top-k pruned tokens (by salience) or increasing M. This feedback loop converges to the smallest token budget that maintains the model’s current reliance on the image for the given prompt.",
  "rationale": "The key to reducing VLM latency is to shrink the cross-attention’s visual KV memory online, but only where the image contributes little to the current next-token distribution. The dependency measure provides an annotation-free, per-step signal of how much the model still needs the image; using it to schedule pruning avoids brittle, one-size-fits-all budgets. Within a given budget, attention-weighted clustering preserves the tokens that matter for the prompt while merging redundant, spatially similar patches, which directly cuts the number of visual keys/values without modifying the encoder.\n\nFinally, once the model’s reliance on the image fades, compressing the visual memory to a handful of virtual conditioning slots replaces many tokens with a compact prefix-style representation. This maintains the conditioning pathway with constant-time cross-attention while avoiding retraining by using per-instance low-rank approximations derived from the model’s own attention statistics.",
