  "method": "We propose Token Triage and Prototype Merge (T2PM), a training-free, plug-in module that sits between the frozen vision encoder and the language model. Given N visual tokens from the frozen encoder, T2PM selects a small, text-relevant core set and merges the rest into a handful of prototypes so the language model only attends to K≪N tokens. The module is budget-aware (target K) and fully deterministic, adding only light-weight matrix ops and nearest-neighbor assignments.\n\nStage A — Hierarchical screening with text conditioning: First, compute a cheap, unconditional saliency for each visual token. If encoder attention maps are available (e.g., CLS→patch), use attention rollout to score tokens; otherwise combine simple cues (token feature norm, local non-maximum suppression over the spatial grid, and self-similarity centrality to downweight near-duplicates). Retain the top C≈2–3K candidates. Next, text-condition the scores without changing any weights: project visual tokens into the language space using the model’s frozen vision-to-LLM adaptor, form a compact text query embedding from the prompt (e.g., mean of its first few hidden states), and compute token–text affinities (dot products or a one-step cross-attention). Rank candidates by a blend of unconditional saliency, text affinity, and uniqueness (e.g., distance from nearest neighbor to spare rare/outlier details). To avoid O(C log C) sorts and all-pairs comparisons, perform m right-to-left adjacent comparison passes over the candidate list, swapping neighbors when the right token has higher blended score; after a few passes, take the first K′ (K′≤K) as the kept core tokens.\n\nStage B — Prototype merging of redundant tokens with uncertainty safeguards: Anchor K′ prototypes at the kept tokens. Assign every remaining token to its nearest prototype by cosine similarity in the frozen encoder’s token space (or pre-projection space), and aggregate features via similarity-weighted averaging; aggregate positions likewise (weighted by assignment) to update positional encodings and store each prototype’s “mass” (number of absorbed tokens). For safety, compute a simple assignment uncertainty per discarded token (e.g., margin between top-1 and top-2 cosine, or the entropy of the normalized similarities). Tokens with ambiguous assignments or unusually low similarity to all prototypes are promoted back into the kept set until the final budget K is met. The output to the LLM is the K prototype embeddings (kept tokens plus merged prototypes), their updated positions, and optional mass scalars that can be used to rescale value vectors in the first cross-attention.\n\nOptional light refinement in the LLM’s first cross-attention: After the first fusion layer updates the multimodal hidden states, re-evaluate the blended scores using the updated text-conditioned affinities for only the bottom-r fraction of tokens and perform one additional adjacent-pass refinement and merge. This preserves training-free operation while allowing a last-mile correction if the initial text-conditioned scores changed after fusion. The refinement is inexpensive and typically reduces tokens further without notable quality loss.\n\nPractical notes: T2PM does not alter or retrain the vision encoder; it only reads its outputs (and, when available, attention weights) and replaces the raw N tokens with K prototypes before multimodal fusion. For captioning or open-ended prompts with weak text priors, T2PM falls back to unconditional saliency plus uniqueness to select core tokens. All steps are implementable with batched matrix ops and k-NN assignments; the overhead is small relative to the savings from reducing the language model’s cross-attention over visual tokens.",
  "rationale": "Inference latency in VLMs scales roughly linearly with the number of visual tokens the language model must attend to. Many of those tokens are redundant due to spatial smoothness and repeated textures, while only a subset is both unique and relevant to the prompt. T2PM reduces the token count post-encoder—where latency pressure is highest—by combining a text-aware selector (to keep what matters) with prototype merging (to compress redundancy), all without modifying or retraining the encoder.\n\nHierarchical screening makes the selection fast and robust: a cheap unconditional pass trims obvious redundancies, and a lightweight, training-free text-conditioning step prioritizes prompt-relevant regions. Efficient adjacent-pair refinements avoid expensive global sorts. Prototype-based merging preserves information by aggregating similar tokens with position-aware weighting, while an uncertainty safeguard protects small or rare details from being collapsed. The result is a compact, semantics-preserving token set that substantially reduces cross-modal attention cost with minimal implementation overhead and no changes to the frozen encoder.",
