  "method": "SCOPE-V: Spectral Certificate-On-demand Pruning and Expansion is a training-free, plug-in pipeline that replaces most visual tokens with a small, text-conditioned spectral basis plus a few leverage-score exemplars, and then adapts this basis online across early language layers with error certificates and on-demand unpruning. It avoids retraining the vision encoder and circumvents per-token K/V projections by aggregating pruned-token contributions in the pre-projection space.\n\nStep 1 — Query-conditioned spectral condensation: From the frozen vision encoder, collect N tokens X ∈ R^{N×d} and 2D coordinates. Form a text summary vector t by averaging language-side queries at the first vision–language cross-attention call. Compute relevance weights w_i = softmax(λ · (x_i W_k · t)), and build a weighted, mean-centered matrix X_w. Run a fast Frequent-Directions-style sketch (or incremental PCA) to obtain a rank-r orthonormal basis U_r and singular values σ. Construct r spectral tokens s_j = σ_j u_j and keep m exemplar tokens with highest text-conditioned leverage l_i = ||(I − U_r U_r^T)x_i||^2 · w_i. For pruned tokens, compute nonnegative assignment coefficients to the spectral tokens via projection magnitudes a_{ij} = |x_i^T u_j| normalized across j.\n\nStep 2 — Value-preserving aggregation via RBF barycentric routing: To avoid computing W_v and W_k on every pruned token, aggregate them before projection. Build r residual buckets S_j = ∑_{i pruned} π_{ij} x_i, where π_{ij} blends projection-based a_{ij} with a compact RBF kernel over 2D coordinates and feature cosine, ensuring locality. Only the r spectral tokens and m exemplars are passed through the VLM’s linear maps: K,V for spectral tokens are K(s_j), V(s_j) and a residual correction R_j = W_v S_j. Each spectral token’s value becomes Ṽ_j = V(s_j) + α · R_j, where α rescales mass to conserve the summed L1 norm of values from its assigned pruned tokens. Exemplar tokens pass through unchanged. This yields r + m tokens total, while the contributions of all other tokens are preserved linearly without per-token projections.\n\nStep 3 — Discretely-online refinement with prototype-certified unpruning: Run the language model with the condensed set for a short layer interval (e.g., the first one or two cross-attn layers). After the interval, compute a deterministic, prototype-margin certificate over the spectral tokens: treat {s_j} as prototypes in the attended key space and measure, per language position, the entropy or top-2 cosine margin of its attention over prototypes. If uncertainty is high and attention gradients concentrate on a prototype p, on-demand unprune the top-b pruned tokens with largest residual energy toward p (e.g., highest π_{ip}·w_i or leverage). Update the spectral basis discretely-online by rerunning a small-rank Frequent Directions on X using new relevance weights proportional to the actually observed attention, smoothed by an uncertainty-aware EMA; keep r fixed and swap in any new directions with largest singular mass. Proceed in short intervals, repeating certificate→optional unpruning→basis refresh, until the token budget or a low-uncertainty state is reached.\n\nImplementation notes: SCOPE-V is architecture-agnostic and needs only to (a) read the first cross-attn queries to form t, (b) replace the vision token list with {spectral tokens + exemplars}, and (c) inject on-demand tokens at layer boundaries. Complexity is O(N d r) once per image to form U_r and O((r + m) d) per head thereafter. Aggregation is K-nearest in the 2D grid, typically K ≤ 4, and does not require per-token K/V. The method degrades gracefully: if no text is available (captioning, OCR-free modes), it falls back to unconditional spectral condensation (w_i uniform); if the certificate remains high-entropy, the system expands toward the full set under the same interface.",
  "rationale": "The latency bottleneck in VLMs scales with visual token count, but most tokens lie close to a low-dimensional subspace conditioned on the current instruction. Rather than pruning/merging by clustering or attention heuristics, SCOPE-V constructs a text-conditioned spectral basis that linearly spans the information needed by the language queries and replaces thousands of tokens with r directions plus a handful of outlier exemplars. Because attention projections are linear, aggregating pruned-token contributions before the V map preserves their effect with a single projection per basis element, yielding large compute savings without retraining.\n\nTwo additional ingredients make the approach robust and novel. First, a deterministic, prototype-margin certificate over the spectral tokens detects when the condensed representation is ambiguous for the current textual queries, and triggers targeted, on-demand unpruning only where evidence is lacking. Second, the spectral basis is updated discretely-online across early language layers using the attention actually observed, with uncertainty-aware EMA smoothing, so the condensed representation tracks what the model needs as reasoning unfolds—without ever peeking ahead or modifying the frozen encoder. Together, these components provide an anytime, error-aware token reduction mechanism that operates entirely at inference time and is complementary to existing token-selection and merging schemes.",
